The matrix formula_94 is known as the matrix of regression coefficients, while in linear algebra formula_95 is the Schur complement of formula_82 in formula_97.

The matrix of regression coefficients may often be given in transpose form, formula_98, suitable for post-multiplying a row vector of explanatory variables formula_99 rather than pre-multiplying a column vector formula_84. In this form they correspond to the coefficients obtained by inverting the matrix of the normal equations of ordinary least squares (OLS).

== Partial covariance matrix ==
A covariance matrix with all non-zero elements tells us that all the individual random variables are interrelated. This means that the variables are not only directly correlated, but also correlated via other variables indirectly. Often such indirect, common-mode correlations are trivial and uninteresting. They can be suppressed by calculating the partial covariance matrix, that is the part of covariance matrix that shows only the interesting part of correlations.

If two vectors of random variables formula_4 and formula_9 are correlated via another vector formula_103, the latter correlations are suppressed in a matrix
formula_104
The partial covariance matrix formula_105 is effectively the simple covariance matrix formula_106 as if the uninteresting random variables formula_103 were held constant.

== Standard deviation matrix ==
The standard deviation matrix formula_108 is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions. It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix formula_109. 

==Covariance matrix as a parameter of a distribution==
If a column vector formula_84 of formula_111 possibly correlated random variables is jointly normally distributed, or more generally elliptically distributed, then its probability density function formula_112 can be expressed in terms of the covariance matrix formula_113 as follows
formula_114
where formula_115 and formula_116 is the determinant of formula_113.

==Covariance matrix as a linear operator==

Applied to one vector, the covariance matrix maps a linear combination c of the random variables X onto a vector of covariances with those variables: formula_118. Treated as a bilinear form, it yields the covariance between the two linear combinations: formula_119. The variance of a linear combination is then formula_120, its covariance with itself.

Similarly, the (pseudo-)inverse covariance matrix provides an inner product formula_121, which induces the Mahalanobis distance, a measure of the &quot;unlikelihood&quot; of &quot;c&quot;.

==Which matrices are covariance matrices?==
From basic property 4. above, let formula_122 be a formula_123 real-valued vector, then
formula_124
which must always be nonnegative, since it is the variance of a real-valued random variable, so a covariance matrix is always a positive-semidefinite matrix.

The above argument can be expanded as follows:formula_125where the last inequality follows from the observation that formula_126 is a scalar.

Conversely, every symmetric positive semi-definite matrix is a covariance matrix. To see this, suppose formula_127 is a formula_128 symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix. From the finite-dimensional case of the spectral theorem, it follows that formula_127 has a nonnegative symmetric square root, which can be denoted by M1/2. Let formula_4 be any formula_131 column vector-valued random variable whose covariance matrix is the formula_128 identity matrix. Then
formula_133

==Complex random vectors==
The variance of a complex &quot;scalar-valued&quot; random variable with expected value formula_134 is conventionally defined using complex conjugation:
formula_135
where the complex conjugate of a complex number formula_136 is denoted formula_137; thus the variance of a complex random variable is a real number.

If formula_138 is a column vector of complex-valued random variables, then the conjugate transpose formula_139 is formed by &quot;both&quot; transposing and conjugating. In the following expression, the product of a vector with its conjugate transpose results in a square matrix called the covariance matrix, as its expectation:
formula_140
The matrix so obtained will be Hermitian positive-semidefinite, with real numbers in the main diagonal and complex numbers off-diagonal.

;Properties
* The covariance matrix is a Hermitian matrix, i.e. formula_141.
* The diagonal elements of the covariance matrix are real.

===Pseudo-covariance matrix===
For complex random vectors, another kind of second central moment, the pseudo-covariance matrix (also called relation matrix) is defined as follows:
formula_142

In contrast to the covariance matrix defined above, Hermitian transposition gets replaced by transposition in the definition.
Its diagonal elements may be complex valued; it is a complex symmetric matrix.

==Estimation==

If formula_143 and formula_144 are centered data matrices of dimension formula_145 and formula_146 respectively, i.e. with &quot;n&quot; columns of observations of &quot;p&quot; and &quot;q&quot; rows of variables, from which the row means have been subtracted, then, if the row means were estimated from the data, sample covariance matrices formula_147 and formula_148 can be defined to be
formula_149
or, if the row means were known a priori,
formula_150

These empirical sample covariance matrices are the most straightforward and most often used estimators for the covariance matrices, but other estimators also exist, including regularised or shrinkage estimators, which may have better properties.

==Applications==
The covariance matrix is a useful tool in many different areas. From it a transformation matrix can be derived, called a whitening transformation, that allows one to completely decorrelate the data or, from a different point of view, to find an optimal basis for representing the data in a compact way (see Rayleigh quotient for a formal proof and additional properties of covariance matrices).
This is called principal component analysis (PCA) and the Karhunen–Loève transform (KL-transform).

The covariance matrix plays a key role in financial economics, especially in portfolio theory and its mutual fund separation theorem and in the capital asset pricing model. The matrix of covariances among various assets&#x27; returns is used to determine, under certain assumptions, the relative amounts of different assets that investors should (in a normative analysis) or are predicted to (in a positive analysis) choose to hold in a context of diversification.

===Use in optimization===
The evolution strategy, a particular family of Randomized Search Heuristics, fundamentally relies on a covariance matrix in its mechanism. The characteristic mutation operator draws the update step from a multivariate normal distribution using an evolving covariance matrix. There is a formal proof that the evolution strategy&#x27;s covariance matrix adapts to the inverse of the Hessian matrix of the search landscape, up to a scalar factor and small random fluctuations (proven for a single-parent strategy and a static model, as the population size increases, relying on the quadratic approximation).
Intuitively, this result is supported by the rationale that the optimal covariance distribution can offer mutation steps whose equidensity probability contours match the level sets of the landscape, and so they maximize the progress rate.

===Covariance mapping===
In covariance mapping the values of the formula_151 or formula_152 matrix are plotted as a 2-dimensional map. When vectors formula_84 and formula_85 are discrete random functions, the map shows statistical relations between different regions of the random functions. Statistically independent regions of the functions show up on the map as zero-level flatland, while positive or negative correlations show up, respectively, as hills or valleys.

In practice the column vectors formula_155, and formula_156 are acquired experimentally as rows of formula_111 samples, e.g.
formula_158
where formula_159 is the &quot;i&quot;-th discrete value in sample &quot;j&quot; of the random function formula_160. The expected values needed in the covariance formula are estimated using the sample mean, e.g.
formula_161
and the covariance matrix is estimated by the sample covariance matrix
formula_162
where the angular brackets denote sample averaging as before except that the Bessel&#x27;s correction should be made to avoid bias. Using this estimation the partial covariance matrix can be calculated as
formula_163
where the backslash denotes the left matrix division operator, which bypasses the requirement to invert a matrix and is available in some computational packages such as Matlab.
Fig. 1 illustrates how a partial covariance map is constructed on an example of an experiment performed at the FLASH free-electron laser in Hamburg. The random function formula_160 is the time-of-flight spectrum of ions from a Coulomb explosion of nitrogen molecules multiply ionised by a laser pulse. Since only a few hundreds of molecules are ionised at each laser pulse, the single-shot spectra are highly fluctuating. However, collecting typically formula_165 such spectra, formula_166, and averaging them over formula_167 produces a smooth spectrum formula_168, which is shown in red at the bottom of Fig. 1. The average spectrum formula_169 reveals several nitrogen ions in a form of peaks broadened by their kinetic energy, but to find the correlations between the ionisation stages and the ion momenta requires calculating a covariance map.

In the example of Fig. 1 spectra formula_166 and formula_171 are the same, except that the range of the time-of-flight formula_172 differs. Panel a shows formula_173, panel b shows formula_174 and panel c shows their difference, which is formula_175 (note a change in the colour scale). Unfortunately, this map is overwhelmed by uninteresting, common-mode correlations induced by laser intensity fluctuating from shot to shot. To suppress such correlations the laser intensity formula_176 is recorded at every shot, put into formula_156 and formula_178 is calculated as panels d and e show. The suppression of the uninteresting correlations is, however, imperfect because there are other sources of common-mode fluctuations than the laser intensity and in principle all these sources should be monitored in vector formula_156. Yet in practice it is often sufficient to overcompensate the partial covariance correction as panel f shows, where interesting correlations of ion momenta are now clearly visible as straight lines centred on ionisation stages of atomic nitrogen.

===Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy===
Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy employs correlation analysis to obtain 2D spectra of the condensed phase. There are two versions of this analysis: synchronous and asynchronous. Mathematically, the former is expressed in terms of the sample covariance matrix and the technique is equivalent to covariance mapping.

