<doc id="191786" wikidata="Q247204" url="?curid=191786" title="Counting measure">
<text>In mathematics, specifically measure theory, the counting measure is an intuitive way to put a measure on any set – the &quot;size&quot; of a subset is taken to be the number of elements in the subset if the subset has finitely many elements, and infinity formula_1 if the subset is infinite.

The counting measure can be defined on any measurable space (that is, any set formula_2 along with a sigma-algebra) but is mostly used on countable sets.

In formal notation, we can turn any set formula_2 into a measurable space by taking the power set of formula_2 as the sigma-algebra formula_5 that is, all subsets of formula_2 are measurable sets. 
Then the counting measure formula_7 on this measurable space formula_8 is the positive measure formula_9 defined by
